<p>The mechanism matters. With a fixed schedule—say, $2,000 per month into a broad index fund—the investor automatically buys fewer shares when prices are high and more when prices are low. During a decline, falling prices stop looking like proof of failure and start functioning as a source of future accumulation. That mental shift is valuable. It turns volatility from something to fear into something the plan can use.</p>
